<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-297-650  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 297 650.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 2 1990 v7 n13 p5(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lotus' Marketplace to give Mac business users CD-ROM power. (LotusDevelopment Corp announces Lotus Marketplace)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ferranti, Marc.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    LOTS.andO;Product:   Marketplace (Data base) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Software packagesData basesCD-ROMProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Marc FerrantiandM;Lotus Development Corp. plans to put the power of CD ROM data retrieval intothe hands of Macintosh business users with the debut next week of LotusMarketplace, a marketing and sales tool, according to sources briefed by thecompany.andM;Lotus Marketplace consists of two databases -- a list of 7.5 millionbusinesses and a list of 80 million residences -- which will be soldseparately, sources said.andP;  Each database will come with a HyperCard interfaceand software that lets users sort data according to geographical area,income, phone number and other criteria.andM;Designed to help small businesses draw up lists for direct-mail campaigns,the Lotus title fills a gap among Macintosh CD-ROM offerings, which currentlyfocus on the academic market.andM;&quot;Small businesses generally have to turn to information providers like Dun andamp;Bradstreet every time they do a mailing,&quot; said David Atlas, an analyst atmarket-research firm International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass., who wasbriefed on the package.andP;  &quot;The advantage of the Lotus product is that [thebusinesses] control the database, sorting it the way they want for differentmailing campaigns and avoiding having to pay for each list.&quot;andM;A Lotus spokeswoman in Cambridge, Mass., confirmed that Lotus plans to takethe stage with Apple Computer Inc. next week to debut a Mac-based CD ROMproduct for business use.andM;Expected to be shipped midyear, Lotus Marketplace is the company's firstventure in the Mac market since Jazz, an integrated software package that wasreleased in May 1985 but never found an audience, analysts noted.andP;  Lotus hasbeen working on a Mac version of 1-2-3 for years, but has not begun testingit.andM;&quot;The Mac market has been a problem for Lotus, and [Marketplace] is a good wayto get back into it,&quot; said David Marshak, an analyst with The PatriciaSeybold Office Computing Group Inc., a market-research firm in Boston.andM;Each database will cost about $695, with quarterly updates priced at $150,sources said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>